{"add":{"doc":{"id":"e93af3f594570551de592bc94754925eeaad0ec89ac25846c36ffbff7776aa8e","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ea/Adams_Bridge_aerial.jpg/220px-Adams_Bridge_aerial.jpg","previous":[],"after":["Archeological data from the Late Pleistocene in South Asia is vital for our understanding of the evolution of modern human behavior and how early humans spread through the Old World.[10] In prehistoric times, the movement of human and faunal populations from the Indian mainland to Sri Lanka and back took place over the continental shelf shared between the two countries, which from around 7000 BP has been submerged below the Palk Strait and Adam's Bridge.[2][9][11] Being only around 70 m deep, significant reductions in sea level due to climate change, in at least the past 500,000 years, periodically caused the continental shelf to be exposed, forming a land bridge approximately 100 km wide and 50 km long.[9][11]"]}}}